  <h1 class="title-2">2010 - Social Networks</h1>

  <div class="container">
    <p>
      By 2010, social networks had already become a central part of the internet
      experience in the UK. The increasing use of smartphones and mobile
      internet benefited platforms like Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube, making
      it easier than ever for people to stay connected on the go. These
      platforms were not only widely used for personal communication and content
      sharing, but they had also become key drivers of digital culture,
      marketing, and news consumption. The year 2010 saw social networks firmly
      establish themselves as an integral part of daily life for millions of
      people across the UK.
    </p>
    <img src="assets/img/logos.png" alt="Social Networks logos" />
    <p class="text-center">
      Facebook, Youtube and Twitter logos, respectively.
    </p>

    <h2>Facebook's Dominance</h2>
    <p>
      By 2010, Facebook had solidified its position as the UK’s leading social
      networking platform. With nearly 30 million active UK users by the end of
      the year, Facebook was the most popular online space for staying connected
      with friends, family, and colleagues.
    </p>
    <p>
      In 2010, Facebook was evolving from a simple social platform to a key tool
      for social interaction, content sharing, and entertainment. The launch of
      the Facebook Like button that year allowed users to easily engage with
      content, which rapidly spread across websites and blogs. This small
      feature would go on to become a symbol of online engagement and an
      essential metric for gauging popularity across the web.
    </p>
    <p>
      As users interacted more frequently, Facebook became the go-to destination
      not only for socializing but for sharing life events, photos, videos, and
      opinions. Businesses and brands also began to recognize the power of
      Facebook’s social graph to reach and interact with potential customers,
      leading to a surge in the platform’s role as a marketing and advertising
      tool.
    </p>
    <h2>Twitter: The Real-Time News Source</h2>
    <p>
      In 2010, Twitter was quickly gaining traction in the UK as a real-time
      news source. With the rise of smartphones and mobile internet, users could
      now access and tweet from anywhere, leading to an explosion of live
      interactions, from breaking news to personal updates. This marked the year
      that Twitter’s 140-character limit began to gain recognition as the
      perfect tool for rapid, bite-sized content, particularly in breaking news
      scenarios.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the UK, Twitter’s impact was particularly evident in politics and
      social movements. During the 2010 UK general election, political parties
      began using Twitter to directly engage with voters, while citizens and
      activists took to the platform to share opinions and organize protests.
      This helped establish Twitter as a key platform not just for personal
      expression, but for political discourse and social change.
    </p>
    <p>
      Additionally, Twitter's use as a live reporting tool was exemplified
      during events like the London riots of 2011 (though the events unfolded
      just after 2010, Twitter was already a prominent real-time communication
      channel). Even before then, in 2010, Twitter was becoming known for its
      ability to share updates in real time, with hashtags helping to organize
      and track conversations around events.
    </p>
    <h2>YouTube: The Social Video Platform</h2>
    <p>
      By 2010, YouTube was already a dominant force in the UK’s social
      landscape, particularly for sharing and viewing videos. Launched in 2005
      and acquired by Google in 2006, YouTube’s growth by 2010 was explosive,
      with users uploading millions of videos every day. The platform was not
      only a place to share personal content but had also become the home of
      viral videos, music videos, tutorials, and live streams.
    </p>
    <img src="assets/img/me-at-zoo.png" alt="Me at zoo video" />
    <p class="text-center">Me at the zoo, the first YouTube video.</p>
    <p>
      In the UK, YouTube was deeply integrated into social media culture. People
      shared everything from personal vlogs to political commentary and
      entertainment. Major brands, musicians, and celebrities also used the
      platform to engage with their audiences. In 2010, music videos, in
      particular, were incredibly popular on YouTube, with artists gaining major
      visibility through the platform. YouTube was also becoming a key marketing
      channel for businesses, who realized the power of video in reaching and
      engaging audiences.
    </p>
    <p>
      The rise of YouTube celebrities also began around this time, with
      individuals amassing millions of followers by creating content in niches
      like comedy, beauty tutorials, tech reviews, and gaming. These YouTube
      personalities were creating communities within the platform, further
      blending social networking with content creation.
    </p>
    <h2>Social Media's Impact on Communication and Culture</h2>
    <p>
      By 2010, social networks in the UK had evolved into more than just places
      to stay connected with friends. They were increasingly used for sharing
      news, public discourse, and personal expression. As more people engaged
      with Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube, social networks became embedded in
      everyday life, and these platforms reshaped the way people consumed
      information and interacted with one another.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Digital Socializing</b>: Social networks became the primary way people
      stayed connected. Facebook events, status updates, and photo sharing were
      now part of the way people celebrated birthdays, planned trips, or simply
      kept in touch with distant friends and family.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Public Interaction</b>: Twitter, in particular, began to be used as a
      way to comment on current events. Whether it was reacting to TV shows or
      providing commentary on news and sports, it became a primary platform for
      public interaction.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Personal Branding and Influence</b>: By 2010, the idea of personal
      branding began to emerge. Users were more conscious of how they presented
      themselves online, curating profiles, photos, and posts that aligned with
      their identities. Influencers, though not yet a formalized category, began
      to gain recognition for their online presence, particularly on platforms
      like YouTube.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Social Activism</b>: Social media also played a significant role in
      activism. Movements like the #SaveOurNHS campaign and growing
      participation in hashtag activism were gaining momentum, with people using
      social networks to raise awareness of social issues.
    </p>
    <h2>The Commercialization of Social Media</h2>
    <p>
      By 2010, social media platforms were also becoming significant players in
      the advertising and marketing worlds. Businesses in the UK began to
      recognize the importance of having an online presence on social networks.
      Facebook launched Facebook Ads in 2007, but by 2010, social media
      advertising had grown rapidly as companies could precisely target users
      based on their profiles, likes, and activities.
    </p>
    <p>
      Social networks became critical tools for businesses to interact with
      customers, drive sales, and build brand loyalty. Twitter also became an
      essential platform for real-time marketing and customer engagement.
      Companies like Tesco, Nike, and O2 were early adopters of social media,
      using Twitter and Facebook for customer service and marketing campaigns.
    </p>
